These mounts secure my battery tubes inside a backpack, but they can be adapted to mount to a number of surfaces. Nut traps are sized for 8-32, but M5 should work. Mounts are designed to be secured to 2" x 1/8" aluminum strips using standard (1/8") rivets. The tube is held in place via 2" velcro straps- I got mine from mcmaster.   
There is a single pack version and a double pack version. The double pack version requires post print bonding, see pics.  I've included the sketchup files, happy printing!

Honestly, I'm not sure if this constitutes a remix or a new design. I'm calling it a remix because there's no way I could have done this without the original code to follow. I tried to make minimal modifications to its structure so you could see the progression from 2D to 3D. I think it's really cool that OpenSCAD operators like minkowski() and intersection_for() work for 2D and 3D, so that was possible.
This is a 3D extension of the approach of generating 2-dimensional Voronoi diagrams. The idea of shifting and rotating rectangles to find "the set of regions closer to each of the seeds than to any other" was extended to three dimensions by shifting and rotating cubes. The  sphere() and cube() functions replace the circle(), and square() and there is another angle (elevation) for the rotate(). It also uses the original code's idea of shifting the boundaries slightly on the normal vector to give some space between the regions and then rounding them with minkowski(). The space between the regions can be seen by subtracting them from some other solid object.
Like the original code, this uses an intersect_for() loop to generate the union of all regions that are closer to a given point than each of its neighbors. I found this a little difficult to visualize and debug (especially in 3D) unless I sent the number of points very low, like only 2 or 3. Have fun exploring this algorithm!
Update: Fixed some problems with the way the random points were generated so the nuclei would display in the voronoi_sphere() module.

WIP So i needed a Z probe for the e3d cyclops for use with my micromake kossel.
I used an inductive probe but got off readings due to the probe being so far away from the hot end (y -30mm) and effector tilt. So i came up with this. It uses the micromake v3 effector. i modded it for more clearance.
This will let you use a e3d cyclops nozzle as the Z-probe. Set up the same as the micromake effector.
For those that dont know. That means the Z probe offset in firmware will be a positive number. Mines was 0.68 but it all depends on how much the adjustment screw is turn. probe offset inf firmware
X0, Y0, Z0.68
To find the prefect Z offset. start with 0.6 then try a test print. If the nozzle grinds into the bed up the number 0.7.
If the nozzle prints to high then lower the number 0.5
Depends on your firmware you can go up to 3 number after decimal point to get that prefect first layer

It's art!  Good for absolutely nothing.  Kidding aside, it's sort of a Mobius strip made out of a Voronoi network.  I used Qhull to compute the network, a homebrew thickening algorithm to make the struts 3D, then Surface Evolver and (I think) ZBrush to smooth it out.
This is intended for 3D printing.  It requires reasonable resolution and good undercut handling (e.g. ZCorp or Prometal), as it will be very inconvenient to clean supports from inside it.

This is a set of tools I printed to help me form and shape a wooden ring.


First is an expanding disk to hold a ring in place and attach it to a power drill for shaping.
 

I followed an instructable to make bent wooden rings (http://www.instructables.com/id/Bent-Wood-Rings/) and was having trouble making a perfect bevel/comfort fit edge. A microlathe would be the perfect solution, but since I don't have one or want to spend the money to buy one, affixing the ring to a power drill seemed like the next best solution. Insert the 2 semi circle into one end of the ring and tighter the tapered screw until it holds the ring firmly.


I also have a simple round form to wrap the wood around to form the basic ring blank.


Lastly is a 3 pronged tool to hold the ring from the outside for inside finishing and polishing. I didn't actually end up using it as the inner holder was sufficient for me, but a tight rubber band around the outside of the prongs to tighter the grip would be recommended.



As a side note, all tools were made with a ring size 6 1/4 in mind, if you need a different size adjust the outer diameter accordingly.
